 all nyt our coors … with very good ly wether<-b->\r\n\r\n<!--section Translation--><-page118->\r\n\r\nTRANSLATION INCOMING!\r\n\r\n<!--nextpage--><-page119->\r\n<!--section Transcription--><-page119->\r\n\r\nAuguste 1587<-b->\r\nThe fyrst daye of Auguste the wynd being at este southest and we went hens our coors nornortheste being very fayre wether and I toocke the sunne and I found my sellf in 5 degres and 40 mynnyts and we went hens north norteste tyll 6 Aclock at nyt and then we went hens northeste and be est all not being very fayer wether and we ran not above 6 leges thys nyt<-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe second daye the wynd at south and we went hens north este and be este being fayer wether and we went north north este and I tock the sunne and I found mysellfe in 6 degrese and 57 mynnyts and we stud hens north north este all the after noone and all nyt being very lyttyll wynd and we ran not above 6 leges thys after noone and all nyt tyll 6 aclock in the mornyng <-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 3 daye of August the wynd cam at northwest and be north and we stud hens north est wyth a prety galle of wynd and sum shoverd and I toocke the sunne and I found mysellfe in 7 degres and 16 mynnyts  the wynd being at north and we went hens este north este and a good galle and we mad an este and be north way tyll 6 a clock and we ran 7 leges and we myt  ly este north este and we thys nyt an este north way about 3 or 4 leges for it was calme all nyt and sum gym lyttyll wynd\r\n[lm:] thys day at nyt john hard dapartyd hys lyf<-b->\r\n\r\n<!--section Translation--><-page119->\r\n\r\nTRANSLATION INCOMING!\r\n \r\n<!--nextpage--><-page120->\r\n<!--section Transcription--><-page120->\r\n\r\nAuguste 1587<-b->\r\nThe 4 daye of Auguste callm tyll 12 aclocke and then the wynd cam all southerlye and very lyttyll wynd and we went hens north northeste and it proved lyttyll wynd all daye tyll 8 Aclock at nyt and then the wynd dyd fresh and cam all sotherly and so conty nyed all nyt tyll 6 a clock and we mad and north north est way thys 18 ours about 8 leges<-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 5 daye of Auguste the wynd all sother lye with a fayer galle of wynd and rayne all the fore noone and lycke to rayne and all the daye and we went hens north north est all daye and all nyt tyll 6 a clock the nextt mornyng and all thys 24 ours a good gall of wynd that the shyp ran a lege and a hallte and our one with a nother<-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 6 daye of Auguste...The wynd being at southweste and we kypyng an esterly coors for becaus we woulld prevent the north northeste wynds whych doo usually blow at the eylandes of cape de varde we being wythin 80 leges of the eyland of saynte Augoo being north northwest from us<-b->\r\n\r\n<!--section Translation--><-page120->\r\n\r\nTRANSLATION INCOMING!\r\n\r\n<!--nextpage--><-page121->\r\n<!--section Transcription--><-page121->\r\n\r\nAuguste 1587<-b->\r\nThe 7 daye of Auguste the wynd at south weste and we went hens north north este wyth rayne and … we ther and we ran thys daye and thys nyt 24 legges<-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 8 daye of Auguste the wynd at south weste wyth rayne and lyttyll wynd and we went hens north north este tyll 12 a clock and then we went hens north and be este wyth a fayer gall of wynd and the fore noone the made not a bout 4 leges and thys after noone we ran 7 leges and we ran thys nyt 10 leges <-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 9 daye of August the wynd came at este and este south este wyth …wether and many … and I toocke the sune and I found my in 13 degres and 14 mynnyts the sunne being my senyt? and we can thys after noone 6 leges and at 6 aclock we shyped? our coorse north all thys ny It proved lyttyll wynd that we ran not about 4 leges all nyt<-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 10 daye of August the wynd set south southeste and very lyttyll wynd and very hot that the shyp had skant steryng waye and it proved callm all daye and all nyt that the shyp had no storyng waye<-b->\r\n\r\n<!--section Translation--><-page121->\r\n\r\nTRANSLATION INCOMING!\r\n\r\n<!--nextpage--><-page122->\r\n<!--section Transcription--><-page122->\r\n\r\nAugust 1587<-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 11 day of August very callme and no breth of wynd tyll 9 aclock and them the wynd at north north este that we myt ly norweste and norweste and be weste tyll 6 aclock at nyt being very fayr wether and all nyt we coulde ly but west norweste and we made but a weste norweste waye one wyth an 12 leges <-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 12 daye the wynd at north and be weste after the wynd cam that we myt ly nor west and be west all daye and we made a bout 7 or 8 leges for it was but lyttyll wynde and all nyt a prety galle of wynd and we made a norwest and be noth way and we ran 7 leges thys nyt <-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 13 day of August the wynd at este south este and a prety galle of wynd and we went hens north north este and I toocke the sune and I found mysellf in 13 degr and 52 mynnyts and we myt ly nor north este all nyt tyll 6 aclock in the mornyng and we made a north and be weste way all thys nyt <-b->\r\n\r\n<!--section Translation--><-page122->\r\n\r\nTRANSLATION INCOMING!\r\n\r\n<!--nextpage--><-page123->\r\n<!--section Transcription--><-page123->\r\n\r\nAugust 1587<-b->\r\nThe 14 daye of Auguste the wynd at north este and we went hens north north weste and fayer wether and I toocke the sunne and I found mysellf in 14 degres and 32 mynnyts and all the after noone we lay but nor weste and be north and nornorth west tyll 6 a clock at afternoone and we stud hens tyll nnyd? nyt and then the we caste about to to the este ward and we myt ly este and be south all the later parte of the nyt and tyll 9 a the next daye and then the mte mystrustyd hymsellf in hys own rekenynges and doutyd that he was to leward of the eylandes and he axed trustem and trustrum tolde hym that he thought soo and then we caste aboute and we myt lye northweste and sumtyme norwest and be northly and sumtyme nor northweste being very hasy and thyck<-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 15 daye of August at 9 Aclock we cast about to the norward and we myt ly norwest and sumtyme norwest and be north and sumtyme north northweste and we made a norweste way one wyth another tyll 6 Aclock at nyt being ery hasy or els we should a sene the eylandes for I dyd Judge mysellf betwyn bovyssta and mayo At 6 Aclock at nyt and we myt ly north northwest all nyt whych mad a norweste way and we ran thys nyt 9 leges<-b->\r\n\r\n<!--section Translation--><-page123->\r\n\r\nTRANSLATION INCOMING!\r\n\r\n<!--nextpage--><-page124->\r\n<!--section Transcription--><-page124->\r\n\r\nAugust 1587<-b->\r\nThe 16 daye of Auguste the wynd at northeste and northeste and be este and we myt ly north northweste...and our mte was befogged for he would never sycke for the eylandes for if he would abav to the souweste ward he myt a found them but he shapyd a fayer coorse the wynd being so franke and he woulde have berulyd by me I would a layd my lyfe we would not a myste the eylandes and that can All the kompany tesstefye for i spacke I nou in tyme but he woulde never be rulyd by me all thys vyage but wrout contrary agaynst me All the vyage and it hath proved Acordyng to hys workyng and At 12 Aclocke I toocke the sunne and I found mysellfe in 15 degres and 50 mynnyts and we myt ly north northwest all the afternoone and all nyt and we made a northweste way 12 leges thys afternoone and thy nyt<-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 17 daye of August the wynd at northeste and fayer wether and we could not tarb the sunne for It was close? wether and all thys daye we made a nor west way and sun wllap? and all night we made an north west and nte wyth a good shote <-b->\r\n\r\n<!--section Translation--><-page124->\r\n\r\nTRANSLATION INCOMING!\r\n\r\n<!--nextpage--><-page125->\r\n<!--section Transcription--><-page125->\r\n\r\nThe 18 daye of Auguste the wynd at north este and a fresh gall of wynd we going norweste wyth a good shet be cause we wold rumie? hens husstelly for to fet the westerly wynd and we myt ly all daye be nyxt? the nor west and the nor weste and be north and we made a norweste and be weste and hallt apoynt to the westeward and we ran thys daye 12 leges and we made all thys nyt a nor weste and be west waye about 12 or 13 leges <-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 19 day of Auguste the wynd at north este and be north and we stud hens north weste and be north wyth a good galle of wynd and fayer wether and we made north weste waye and we ran 15 leges thys day and a norwest way and all nyt we made a northweste way about 14 or 15 leges <-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 20 daye of Auguste the wynd at north este and be este and we stud hens north north weste wyth a prety shite? and I toocke the sunne and I found mysellf in 20 degrese and 50 mynnyts And at nyt I toocke the star and I found mysellf in 21 degres betwyn 2 and 8 Aclock in the evynyng and we made a north west and be north way all day and all nyt we lay hens north and be north and nor north weste all the nyt and we made a nor west and be north way all nyt and we ran 15 leges thys nyt  <-b->\r\n\r\n<!--section Translation--><-page125->\r\n\r\nTRANSLATION INCOMING!\r\n \r\n<!--nextpage--><-page126->\r\n<!--section Transcription--><-page126->\r\n\r\nAugust 1587<-b->\r\nThe 21 of August the wynd at este north este and a fayer galle of wynd I toocke the sunne and I found my my sellfe in 22 degres 24 menette?I …..? and mad from thys daye 12 aclock tyll the next daye 12 alock an 30 leges and our way was northweste one wyth another<-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 22 daye of august the wynde at este northest and I found myself in the north tropryck and afterward we myt ly norwest all the afternoone ..<-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 23 daye of August the wynd at north and we mad thys 24 ours a north … way and we ran 30 leges <-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 24 daye the wynd north este and lyttyll wynd and I toocke the sunne and I found my sellf in 26 degrese and we stud hens north north west all the after noone and and all nyt be my lyttyll wynd <-b->\r\n\r\n\r\n<!--section Translation--><-page126->\r\n\r\nTRANSLATION INCOMING!\r\n\r\n<!--nextpage--><-page127->\r\n<!--section Transcription--><-page127->\r\n\r\nAuguste 1587<-b->\r\nThe 25 day of Auguste callm the wind beinge att northe and I tock the sonne and I found myself in 26 degrees and 15 mynnetts and we stood hence northweste and be weste and west northwest with very littill wind till 6 aclock at nyght and then Thomas antony caste aboutt to the estewardes to secke for a westerly wind showing this dudlinge one of his marry nere trickes and within one hower I called the captyn and casted him to caste about fore I toold him yf he did stand this waye he would starve all the reste of the companye for we could ly butt este and be northe with a saylle which would nott feche the cannaryes  unlesse that we should agone for cap blanke wher was nothing to be gotton and then I cassed the captyn to casse them to caste about he yf he did <-b->\r\n[68] August 1587<-b->\r\nlove his owne lyfe and the companyee and then we myght lye weste northe weste and northweste and be weste which provinge within on hower calme al the nyght<-b->\r\nThe 26 Auguste being very callme till /11/ aclock in the fore noone and then the wind came att south and south west and at west with very litill wind and we tock the sonne and we found that we had passed nothine for yt was very callme and from 12 aclock we went hence north and be este the wind beinge at west northe[west] we goinge hence north and be.. with very litill wind all this [after]none and all nyght we stoud hence northe till /12/aclock the next daye<-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 27 Auguste the wind beinge att southweste and I tock the sonne and I found my selfe in 27/ degres /52/ menettes and all the after none we went northe and be este all the nyght we went hence northe<-b->\r\n\r\n<!--section Translation--><-page127->\r\n\r\nTRANSLATION INCOMING!\r\n\r\n<!--nextpage--><-page128->\r\n<!--section Transcription--><-page128->\r\n\r\nAuguste 1586[sic]<-b->\r\nThe 28 of Auguste the wind beinge at southe west and we goinge hence northe and be este with a fayre gall of wind and I tockk the sonn and I found mysellfe in 29 degres and 29 mynette and all nyt we ran north and be este <-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 29 of Auguste the wind beinge at south south and este afayr gall of wind I could not tack the sone and I judged my sellfe that the shep? rane 36 leage this 24 hu?ere worth and be ete? and north north este on ? our waye so<-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 30 daye the wynd west north west our? stem north and by est and somntyms no northest we maid good our way north est and by north after my jugment 30 ? the sonne observed I found myself in 33 33 mynnyts <-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 31 daye the wynd changed dyrectyons in the ney?est we maid our way north and by est the sonne observed I found myselfe in 35 - 21<-b->\r\n…\r\n\r\n<!--section Translation--><-page128->\r\n\r\nTRANSLATION INCOMING!\r\n\r\n<!--nextpage--><-page129->\r\n<!--section Transcription--><-page129->\r\n\r\nThe first of september the wind este from the laste …? the firste of this p[re]sentt?  and 40 league <-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 2 of September being at este and be northe we went hence north and be weste and we mad first daye /12/aclocke till this daye 12 aclocke we ran 40 league with very muche wind to and this 2 dayes we could nott tacke the sone --- and from 12 a clock tyll 6 aclock at nyte the shyp ? mad? a north north ? way /7/ leages and we ? our fore saylle and layde ?try 5 orurs and and ? way /5/ leages and then the wynd wesstered<-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 3 daye of September wynd at south weste and w[e] went hens north este and est north este all the daye till 6 aclock att night and these 18 howers she mad a north este and be este waye /12/ leage and ? she dyd att nyght till the next daye 12 aclocke<-b->\r\n\r\n<!--section Translation--><-page129->\r\n\r\nTRANSLATION INCOMING!\r\n\r\n<!--nextpage--><-page130->\r\n<!--section Transcription--><-page130->\r\n\r\nThe 4 of september the wind  at weste and we tocke the sonne in 40 degres 55 mynetts and so we stoud hence este north este all the daye and at nyght till 12 aclocke the next daye<-b->   \r\n<-b->\r\nThe 5 of September the wind att south and we stoud hence este northe este att 12 aclock  I tocke the sonne and I found my sellfe in 41 degres 55 mynettes  ? and so we stoud hence all the after none and all nyght este north este with a frayshe gall of wind<-b->\r\n<-b->\r\nThe 6 of September the wind at south south weste and we went hence este north este with a frishe gall and all nyght till 12 a clock the next daye and she ran 30 leage <-b->\r\n[70]\r\nThe 7 of september the [wind]? att south south weste being littill wind and I tocke the sone and I found myself in 43 degrees 20 mynetts and all the daye after yt proved? callme<-b->\r\n<-b->\r\n~Thomas Holmes [?]<-b->\r\n\r\n<!--section Translation--><-page130->\r\n\r\nTRANSLATION INCOMING!', 'The Journal of Thomas Hood', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'hoods-journal', '', '', '2018-03-06 16:43:06', '2018-03-06 16:43:06', '', 0, 'http://www.scg52.com/Archive/?p=7', 0, 'post', '', 0);
